    <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-12 project__list--label">
      <h3>Jumper</h3>
      <h5>
        <p>Jumper is a collaborative project aimed towards rating team-orientated entertainment venues. Rock climbing, Escape the Room, and sky diving are some of the venues rated. Technologies used were Rails, Foundation, MiniTest and PostgreSQL.</p>
        <p>Key lessons that I took away from this project were leading a team of four junior developers, and expanding my css knowledge of emebeded videos, positioning elements, and animations.</p>
      </h5>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-12 project__list--label">
      <h3>WingMe</h3>
      <h5>
        <p>WingMe is a dating app where instead of you matching yourself, your friends to match you.</p>
        <p>WingMe is a project aimed at helping singles connect in the most organic way possible - through friends.
        Some libraries I experimented with were Masonry.js, Devise, Kaminari, PG Search, and Facebook API Authentication.</p>
        <p>A key challenge was creating user-to-user (self-referential) associations for the friend and match system. Adding another user and referencing them required some ActiveRecord trickery.
        Some other lessons learned were overriding Foundations fixed grid system with Masonry.js flexible grid system, and integrating Devise authentication with Facebook Authentication. The latter was my first experience getting two different API's to work together.</p>
      </h5>
    </div>
