      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-12 project__list--label">
      <h3>CS:GO Webcrawler</h3>
      <h5>
        <p>This webcrawler was a project for a good friend. The focus was to parse and export into a CSV win rates, items gambled, and who gambled the items</p>
        <p>An interesting problem I encountered on this project was how to architect the data. When iterating through the websites I was given the choice to use either an array of hashes or an array of objects. An array of objects was chosen because it would have scalability. It’s significantly easier to manipulate objects as opposed to hashes in Ruby.
        <p>On this project I took my first dive into Nokogiri and by extension, Xpath. The XML/HTML parsing functions helped pick out usernames and items. The extraction code was placed inside of a loop that executed at a certain interval and pushed the information to Google Docs (shout out to Chrome’s developer tools to help me navigate through the Document Object Model aka DOM).</p>
      </h5>
    </div>
  </div>

